{"cursor":"9796","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Joseph Philippe Lemercier Laroche image = birth_name = Joseph Philippe\n| Lemercier Laroche birth_date = birth_place = Cap Haiten, Haiti death_date =\n| death_place = Atlantic Ocean occupation = Engineer\n}}\n\n'Joseph Philippe Lemercier Laroche' (May 26, 1886 – April 15, 1912) was a\nParis-educated Haitian engineer. He was the only black passenger on the ill-\nfated voyage of the RMS ''Titanic''. [http://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/titanic-\nbiography/joseph-laroche.html Encyclopedia-titanica.org] [http://www.titanic-\ntitanic.com/joseph_philippe_lemercier_laroche.shtml Titanic-\ntitanic.com] W. Mae Kent, [http://www.blackpast.org/?q=gah/laroche-joseph-phillipe-lemercier-1889-\n1912 Laroche, Joseph Phillipe Lemercier (1889-1912)] at Blackpast.org He\ngot his pregnant French wife and their two daughters onto a lifeboat; they\nsurvived, but he himself did not.\n\nAt the age of 15, he was sent to Beauvais, France to study. After he graduated\nwith an engineering degree, he married Frenchwoman Juliette Lafargue. However, he was unable to find work matching his qualifications due\nto the color of his skin in a racist society. Tired of living\noff of his wine seller father-in-law, he decided to return to Haiti with his\ngrowing family. His uncle, Cincinnatus Leconte, the President of Haiti, arranged a job for him as a math teacher.\n\nHis mother purchased first class passage for them aboard the liner [[SS France\n(1910)|La France]]. When he and his wife learned of the Compagnie GÃ©nÃ©rale\nTransatlantique's policy against children dining with their parents, they\nexchanged their tickets for a second class passage aboard the Titanic.\n\nLaroche died in the sinking of the Titanic. His body was never recovered. His\nwife returned to Paris with her daughters Louise and Simonne Laroche and gave\nbirth to their son, Joseph Lemercier Laroche.\n\nLaroche, a three-act opera based on his life, was an official part of the 2003\nNational Black Arts Festival and was scheduled to premiere at the Callanwolde\nFine Arts Center on July 18.\n\n {{Infobox person| name =\nLouise Laroche\n| birth_date = birth_place = Paris, France death_date = death_place = Paris,\n| France parents = Joseph Philippe Lemercier Laroche and Juliette Marie Louise\n| Lafargue\n}}\n","linknr":217,"url":"Joseph_Philippe_Lemercier_Laroche","recorded":1375071951,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Joseph_Philippe_Lemercier_Laroche&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Joseph_Philippe_Lemercier_Laroche&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:JosephLaroche.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/6c/JosephLaroche.jpg","/wiki/File:JosephLaroche.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Haiti","/wiki/Atlantic_Ocean","/wiki/Engineer","/wiki/Paris","/wiki/Haiti","/wiki/Black_people","/wiki/RMS_Titanic","#cite_note-Ebony-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","#cite_note-Ebony-1","/wiki/Beauvais","/wiki/France","#cite_note-Ebony-1","#cite_note-Ebony-1","/wiki/Cincinnatus_Leconte","/wiki/List_of_heads_of_state_of_Haiti","#cite_note-Ebony-1","/wiki/SS_France_(1910)","